  "prompt": "What's a good video editor for windows?",
  "response": "There are several excellent video editors available for Windows, depending on your needs, skill level, and budget. Here are some of the best options:\n\n---\n\n### **For Beginners:**\n1. **Microsoft Photos (Free)**  \n   - Built into Windows 10 and 11.  \n   - Simple interface for basic trimming, splitting, and adding text or music.  \n   - Great for quick edits and basic projects.\n\n2. **Clipchamp (Free or Paid)**  \n   - Web-based and also available as a Windows app.  \n   - User-friendly with templates, effects, and stock media.  \n   - Free version has watermark; paid plans remove it and unlock more features.\n\n3. **Shotcut (Free, Open-Source)**  \n   - Beginner-friendly with a clean interface.  \n   - Supports a wide range of formats and features like transitions, filters, and keyframes.  \n\n---\n\n### **For Intermediate Users:**\n4. **DaVinci Resolve (Free or Paid)**  \n   - Professional-grade editor with advanced color grading, audio post-production, and VFX tools.  \n   - Free version is incredibly powerful; paid Studio version adds advanced features.  \n   - Steeper learning curve but worth it for serious creators.\n\n5. **HitFilm Pro (Free or Paid)**  \n   - Combines video editing with visual effects and compositing.  \n   - Free version is robust; paid versions include more tools and features.  \n\n6. **VEGAS Pro (Paid)**  \n   - Popular among YouTubers and content creators.  \n   - Intuitive workflow with powerful editing tools and effects.  \n   - Often goes on sale, making it more affordable.  \n\n---\n\n### **For Advanced/Professional Users:**\n7. **Adobe Premiere Pro (Paid, Subscription)**  \n   - Industry-standard video editor with a vast array of tools and integrations.  \n   - Perfect for complex projects, multi-camera editing, and collaboration.  \n\n8. **Final Cut Pro (Paid, but Windows users can access via boot camp or virtualization)**  \n   - While primarily for Mac, some Windows users use it through workarounds.  \n   - Known for its speed, efficiency, and professional features.  \n\n---\n\n### **Bonus Tools:**\n9. **Camtasia (Paid)**  \n   - Great for screen recording and tutorial videos.  \n   - Includes simple editing tools, transitions, and annotations.  \n\n10. **Kdenlive (Free, Open-Source)**  \n    - Feature-rich editor with multi-track support, effects, and transitions.  \n    - Suitable for intermediate users looking for a free alternative.  \n\n---\n\n### **What to Consider:**  \n- **Budget:** Free editors like DaVinci Resolve and Shotcut are excellent for most users.  \n- **Features:** Choose based on your needs (e.g., color grading, VFX, or simple cuts).  \n- **Learning Curve:** Beginners should start with simpler tools like Clipchamp or Microsoft Photos.  \n\nFor most users, **DaVinci Resolve** (free) or **Adobe Premiere Pro** (paid) are the top recommendations.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
